    "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/fda-pump-experimental-hemolysis",
    "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/monte-carlo-uq-samples"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/pump-hemolysis-baseline",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "FDA pump hemolysis baseline validation — 5 operating points",
      "description": "CFD hemolysis index predictions compared against experimental measurements from the FDA generic centrifugal pump benchmark dataset at 5 flow-speed operating conditions. The UQ campaign (2500-sample Monte Carlo) was conducted alongside this validation activity and confirmed sensitivity of hemolysis predictions to inlet turbulence intensity and blood viscosity parameters. Prediction intervals overlap experimental scatter at 3 of 5 operating points; 2 points show systematic over-prediction exceeding 40% relative error. Validation metric: GCI-corrected normalized RMS error = 0.38 (required ≤ 0.20 for MRL 5)."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/mesh-convergence-study",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh convergence and discretization error quantification",
      "description": "Three-level mesh refinement study on the FDA pump geometry (coarse: 2.1M cells, medium: 8.4M cells, fine: 33.6M cells). Grid convergence index (GCI) computed for hemolysis index QoI. Fine-mesh GCI = 12.3%, exceeding the MRL 5 requirement of ≤ 5%. Oscillatory convergence observed in the impeller trailing-edge region, indicating unresolved turbulence-hemolysis coupling. Discretization error remains a primary credibility gap."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/model-form-assessment",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Turbulence model form uncertainty assessment",
      "description": "Comparison of SST k-omega, realizable k-epsilon, and LES sub-grid scale model predictions for shear stress distribution in the pump volute. Model form uncertainty estimated at ±28% for peak shear stress magnitude relevant to hemolysis calculation. The Monte Carlo UQ campaign incorporated turbulence model coefficients as uncertain inputs; however, the structured sensitivity analysis linking individual parameter perturbations to hemolysis QoI variance was not captured in a machine-readable evidence artifact. Narrative summary only."
    }
  ],
  "wasDerivedFrom": "https://doi.org/10.1115/1.4042689",
